(26,	1,	'2025-02-27 19:00:00',	'2025-02-27 19:00:00',	'<p>Snacking doesn\'t have to mean reaching for a bag of crisps. With a little planning, your between-meal bites can be as nourishing as your main meals.</p>\n\n<p>One of our favourite quick snacks is a handful of organic mixed nuts paired with a piece of seasonal fruit. The healthy fats from the nuts help slow the absorption of natural sugars from the fruit, keeping your energy stable and your hunger at bay.</p>\n\n<p>Another go-to is homemade granola bars. Combine organic oats, nut butter, honey and a handful of dried fruits, press into a tray and refrigerate overnight. In the morning you have a week\'s worth of snacks ready to grab and go.</p>\n\n<p>For something savoury, try rice cakes topped with organic hummus and sliced cucumber. It\'s light, crunchy, and satisfying without the mid-afternoon energy crash.</p>\n\n<p>The key to healthy snacking is preparation. Spend twenty minutes on a Sunday sorting your snacks for the week, and you\'ll find it far easier to make good choices when hunger strikes.</p>',	'Healthy Snack Ideas',	'Quick and easy organic snack recipes to fuel your day and keep you energized throughout.',	'publish',	'open',	'open',	'',	'healthy-snack-ideas',	'',	'',	'2026-03-09 08:05:13',	'2026-03-09 08:05:13',	'',	0,	'http://server-coomendem.local/healthy-snack-ideas/',	0,	'post',	'',	0),
(27,	1,	'2025-02-17 19:00:00',	'2025-02-17 19:00:00',	'<p>Food labels can be overwhelming, but understanding them is one of the most powerful tools you have for making healthier choices. Manufacturers are required to list ingredients in order of weight — so the first ingredient is the most abundant.</p>\n\n<p>Watch out for sugar hiding under different names: glucose syrup, dextrose, fructose, maltose and corn syrup are all forms of added sugar. A product might list five different sugars separately so that none appears near the top of the ingredients list — a common trick worth knowing.</p>\n\n<p>The nutrition panel shows values per 100g and per serving. Always check the per-100g column when comparing products, as serving sizes can be manipulated to make a product look healthier than it is.</p>\n\n<p>Organic certification labels — such as the EU organic logo or the Soil Association mark — are regulated and meaningful. Claims like \"natural\" or \"wholesome\" have no legal definition and can be applied to almost anything.</p>\n\n<p>With practice, label reading becomes second nature. Start with products you buy regularly, and you may be surprised by what you find.</p>',	'A Guide to Reading Food Labels',	'Learn what to look for on food labels and how to spot hidden sugars, additives and misleading claims.',	'publish',	'open',	'open',	'',	'guide-to-reading-food-labels',	'',	'',	'2026-03-09 08:05:51',	'2026-03-09 08:05:51',	'',	0,	'http://server-coomendem.local/guide-to-reading-food-labels/',	0,	'post',	'',	0),
(28,	1,	'2025-02-09 19:00:00',	'2025-02-09 19:00:00',	'<p>Nuts are among the most nutrient-dense foods available, packing protein, healthy fats, fibre and a wide range of vitamins and minerals into a small, portable package.</p>\n\n<p>Almonds are the go-to for sustained energy. Rich in vitamin E, magnesium and slow-releasing carbohydrates, a small handful before a workout or a long meeting can keep you focused and fuelled for hours.</p>\n\n<p>Walnuts stand out for their omega-3 content — unusually high for a plant food. These essential fats support brain health and reduce inflammation, making walnuts a smart daily habit.</p>\n\n<p>Cashews are lower in fat than most nuts and rich in iron and zinc, making them particularly valuable for people following a plant-based diet. Their creamy texture also makes them a versatile ingredient in cooking.</p>\n\n<p>Buying organic matters more with nuts than many people realise. Conventional nuts are often heavily treated with fungicides during storage. Organic certification ensures a cleaner product from farm to bag.</p>',	'Best Organic Nuts for Energy',	'Almonds, walnuts, cashews — we break down which nuts give you the best nutritional bang for your buck.',	'publish',	'open',	'open',	'',	'best-organic-nuts-for-energy',	'',	'',	'2026-03-09 08:06:07',	'2026-03-09 08:06:07',	'',	0,	'http://server-coomendem.local/best-organic-nuts-for-energy/',	0,	'post',	'',	0),
(29,	1,	'2025-01-29 19:00:00',	'2025-01-29 19:00:00',	'<p>Cold-pressed juice has become a premium product in health food stores, but the price difference compared to standard pasteurized juice raises a fair question: is it actually better for you?</p>\n\n<p>The case for cold-pressing is rooted in the production process. Traditional juicers generate heat through friction, which can degrade heat-sensitive vitamins and enzymes. Cold-press machines use hydraulic pressure to extract juice slowly, preserving more nutrients in the final product.</p>\n\n<p>Pasteurization — heating juice to kill bacteria — extends shelf life significantly but does reduce certain vitamins, particularly vitamin C and some B vitamins. The extent depends on temperature and duration.</p>\n\n<p>In terms of taste, cold-pressed juices tend to have a fresher, more vibrant flavour. The difference is most noticeable with green juices and delicate fruit blends.</p>\n\n<p>The trade-off is shelf life and cost. Cold-pressed juices typically last three to five days refrigerated and cost significantly more to produce. For everyday drinking, a good quality pasteurized organic juice is still a healthy choice. Cold-pressed is worth the premium when you want maximum nutrition in a specific blend.</p>',	'Cold-Pressed vs Pasteurized Juice',	'Is cold-pressed really worth the premium? We compare nutrition, taste and shelf life side by side.',	'publish',	'open',	'open',	'',	'cold-pressed-vs-pasteurized-juice',	'',	'',	'2026-03-09 08:06:26',	'2026-03-09 08:06:26',	'',	0,	'http://server-coomendem.local/cold-pressed-vs-pasteurized-juice/',	0,	'post',	'',	0),
(30,	1,	'2025-01-19 19:00:00',	'2025-01-19 19:00:00',	'<p>Seasonal eating means choosing foods that are naturally ready to harvest at the time you\'re buying them. It sounds simple — and it is — but the benefits ripple out in ways that might surprise you.</p>\n\n<p>Produce picked in season and sold locally travels far shorter distances, which means it reaches you fresher and with more of its nutrients intact. Out-of-season produce is often picked early and ripened artificially in transit, which affects both flavour and nutritional value.</p>\n\n<p>Seasonally grown food is also less resource-intensive. Growing strawberries in a heated greenhouse in January requires enormous amounts of energy. The same strawberries grown outdoors in June are far more environmentally efficient.</p>\n\n<p>Getting started is straightforward. Visit a local farmers\' market and buy what\'s available — that\'s your seasonal guide right there. Alternatively, look up a seasonal food calendar for your region and use it when planning your weekly meals.</p>\n\n<p>Seasonal eating also naturally connects you to variety. When you commit to eating what\'s available now, you find yourself cooking with ingredients you might otherwise overlook — and that\'s where some of the best discoveries happen.</p>',	'Seasonal Eating: A Beginner is Guide',	'Eating with the seasons is better for your body and the planet. Here\'s how to get started simply.',	'publish',	'open',	'open',	'',	'seasonal-eating-guide',	'',	'',	'2026-03-09 08:13:21',	'2026-03-09 08:13:21',	'',	0,	'http://server-coomendem.local/seasonal-eating-guide/',	0,	'post',	'',	0),
